WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.490
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.976 --> 00:00:08.964
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:11.952 --> 00:00:12.948
BD WONG: Hey.

00:00:12.948 --> 00:00:14.442
Hello, everybody.

00:00:14.442 --> 00:00:14.942
JULIE: Hi.

00:00:14.942 --> 00:00:17.234
BD WONG: Julie, did you just
say that I would volunteer

00:00:17.234 --> 00:00:18.540
to take selfies with everybody?

00:00:18.540 --> 00:00:19.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:19.460 --> 00:00:22.340
JULIE: Well, yes, kind of.

00:00:22.340 --> 00:00:24.340
BD WONG: Do you see how
many people are in here?

00:00:24.340 --> 00:00:25.180
JULIE: Well, yeah.

00:00:25.180 --> 00:00:27.380
I mean, we're Google, so
we can be very efficient.

00:00:27.380 --> 00:00:29.420
We can streamline this process.

00:00:29.420 --> 00:00:30.970
[LAUGHS]

00:00:30.970 --> 00:00:33.220
BD WONG: How about if we
take a selfie with one person

00:00:33.220 --> 00:00:34.928
and then green screen
in everyone's face?

00:00:34.928 --> 00:00:36.530
JULIE: OK, we can
do that, for sure.

00:00:36.530 --> 00:00:38.450
All of the people that want
to be in that selfie, right?

00:00:38.450 --> 00:00:40.575
BD WONG: No, I'm happy to
take selfies, it's just--

00:00:40.575 --> 00:00:42.325
I'm just razzing you.

00:00:42.325 --> 00:00:43.255
JULIE: OK, thank you.

00:00:43.255 --> 00:00:46.180
Raz some more if you want, so.

00:00:46.180 --> 00:00:46.948
How are you?

00:00:46.948 --> 00:00:47.740
BD WONG: I'm great.

00:00:47.740 --> 00:00:48.160
JULIE: Yeah?

00:00:48.160 --> 00:00:48.702
BD WONG: Yes.

00:00:48.702 --> 00:00:50.950
You know, I'm-- you said
this already, right?

00:00:50.950 --> 00:00:52.580
I'm a native San Franciscan.

00:00:52.580 --> 00:00:56.710
So it's great to come home.

00:00:56.710 --> 00:01:00.393
And it's great for my mom to
come home and do a play in--

00:01:00.393 --> 00:01:01.060
JULIE: Oh, yeah.

00:01:01.060 --> 00:01:02.768
BD WONG: My hometown
and stuff like that.

00:01:02.768 --> 00:01:06.940
It's not really-- it's a big
deal for my family, kind of.

00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:07.940
So I love it.

00:01:07.940 --> 00:01:09.010
And I love this theater.

00:01:09.010 --> 00:01:11.380
I've always loved this
particular theater--

00:01:11.380 --> 00:01:13.060
American Conservatory
Theater, ACT.

00:01:13.060 --> 00:01:18.190
And I-- so this is a really
great kind of collaboration

00:01:18.190 --> 00:01:22.380
with them that allows me to
have this hometown experience

00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:25.750
and to do a play like
this one that I really--

00:01:25.750 --> 00:01:28.720
I really believe a lot
in this particular play.

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:31.790
JULIE: Yeah, so let's talk a
little bit more about the play.

00:01:31.790 --> 00:01:32.290
BD WONG: OK.

00:01:32.290 --> 00:01:33.790
JULIE: I got to see
it on Wednesday.

00:01:33.790 --> 00:01:34.768
It was fantastic.

00:01:34.768 --> 00:01:35.560
BD WONG: Oh, great.

00:01:35.560 --> 00:01:36.640
JULIE: Yeah.

00:01:36.640 --> 00:01:40.445
But I'm hoping more people here
and folks on the live stream

00:01:40.445 --> 00:01:41.320
would come to see it.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:44.020
So can you tell us a
little bit about the show?

00:01:44.020 --> 00:01:44.830
BD WONG: Yes.

00:01:44.830 --> 00:01:48.150
Well, Lauren-- Lauren
Yee is the playwright.

00:01:48.150 --> 00:01:50.600
Lauren Yee is also a
native San Franciscan.

00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:51.100
JULIE: Yes.

00:01:51.100 --> 00:01:52.600
BD WONG: If you know anything--

00:01:52.600 --> 00:01:54.308
I mean, there was a
big article about her

00:01:54.308 --> 00:01:56.320
in the pink section on Sunday.

00:01:56.320 --> 00:01:59.380
But very briefly, she
really writes a lot

00:01:59.380 --> 00:02:01.930
from her own experience
and her own family,

00:02:01.930 --> 00:02:03.880
and has written
two plays, in fact,

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:07.090
that are inspired in one way
or another by her father.

00:02:07.090 --> 00:02:09.699
This particular play
is inspired by the fact

00:02:09.699 --> 00:02:12.130
that her father played
basketball in Chinatown

00:02:12.130 --> 00:02:15.250
in the early '70s and was
on a basketball team of kids

00:02:15.250 --> 00:02:17.320
from San Francisco
Chinatown that

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:21.190
went to China to play exhibition
games throughout China.

00:02:21.190 --> 00:02:24.880
And so she's written a
play about a young, very

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:28.750
enthusiastic Asian-American
boy in high school

00:02:28.750 --> 00:02:34.540
who, like, wills his way onto
the team to go play in China

00:02:34.540 --> 00:02:37.180
and kind of have
this kind of what's

00:02:37.180 --> 00:02:41.410
it like for an Asian-American
kid to go to China experience.

00:02:41.410 --> 00:02:43.450
And there's a lot
more to the play

00:02:43.450 --> 00:02:45.760
and a lot more is
revealed in the play.

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:49.000
But the play also centers
around the relationship

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:51.430
between two basketball
coaches, a Chinese basketball

00:02:51.430 --> 00:02:53.170
coach and an American
basketball coach.

00:02:53.170 --> 00:02:55.830
And I play the Chinese
basketball coach.

00:02:55.830 --> 00:02:57.252
So that's it, basically.

00:02:57.252 --> 00:02:58.240
JULIE: OK, basically.

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:01.030
BD WONG: And also
in its identity,

00:03:01.030 --> 00:03:05.590
it's a comedy with a really
strong emotional undercurrent,

00:03:05.590 --> 00:03:07.780
which is very rare
in plays to me.

00:03:07.780 --> 00:03:09.910
I find the most
successful plays,

00:03:09.910 --> 00:03:12.340
plays that are
successfully funny

00:03:12.340 --> 00:03:14.530
and move you at the same time.

00:03:14.530 --> 00:03:15.640
Did you find it that way?

00:03:15.640 --> 00:03:16.450
JULIE: I did, yes.

00:03:16.450 --> 00:03:19.720
And I find that Lauren's
work in particular, she just

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:21.970
did "King of the Yees" at
SF Playhouse, which is also

00:03:21.970 --> 00:03:23.770
another story about Larry--

00:03:23.770 --> 00:03:24.830
BD WONG: Yes.

00:03:24.830 --> 00:03:26.800
JULIE: --but I
really like her work

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:31.270
because she does straddle humor
and touching some soft points

00:03:31.270 --> 00:03:33.580
about family relationships,
which I think

00:03:33.580 --> 00:03:35.217
is really heartwarming
about her work.

00:03:35.217 --> 00:03:35.800
BD WONG: Yeah.

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:37.008
She's really skilled in that.

00:03:37.008 --> 00:03:38.560
And the extra added--

00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:39.537
I mean, I really--

00:03:39.537 --> 00:03:41.370
I'm here to sell tickets,
right, of course--

00:03:41.370 --> 00:03:42.070
JULIE: Please.

00:03:42.070 --> 00:03:42.570
Please do.

00:03:42.570 --> 00:03:44.080
BD WONG: --but I
really-- do really,

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:47.260
sincerely recommend
this experience

00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:50.410
of seeing this play
in San Francisco.

00:03:50.410 --> 00:03:52.750
And also, it's too late
to see "King of the Yees"

00:03:52.750 --> 00:03:54.370
at the San Francisco Playhouse,
but I would definitely

00:03:54.370 --> 00:03:55.530
have recommended that.

00:03:55.530 --> 00:03:59.890
And when I went to see
it, "King of the Yees,"

00:03:59.890 --> 00:04:02.860
I sat there thinking, how
was this play ever done

00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:04.170
anywhere but in San Francisco?

00:04:04.170 --> 00:04:06.610
The resonance was so strong.

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:10.420
The places that she mentions,
the locations, the things

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:12.430
that we all know,
or that many of us

00:04:12.430 --> 00:04:16.360
know that we draw from our
own childhood experiences

00:04:16.360 --> 00:04:20.110
are really strong.

00:04:20.110 --> 00:04:22.810
And they're much stronger-- you
know, this play has been done--

00:04:22.810 --> 00:04:24.190
"King of the Yees"
and "The Great Leap"

00:04:24.190 --> 00:04:25.840
have been done all
over the country,

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:28.060
but there's something really
special about seeing San

00:04:28.060 --> 00:04:29.352
Francisco productions about it.

00:04:29.352 --> 00:04:30.750
They're going to be rare.

00:04:30.750 --> 00:04:32.590
It's not-- it's a
rare opportunity.

00:04:32.590 --> 00:04:35.880
But the one thing that I
think you might have noticed

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:38.560
is that the audiences
kind of like--

00:04:38.560 --> 00:04:40.750
they just get such a
kick out of hearing

00:04:40.750 --> 00:04:42.700
about things that they know.

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:45.470
And that's not an experience
you can have that often.

00:04:45.470 --> 00:04:48.430
And I think one of the things
that regional theater does when

00:04:48.430 --> 00:04:51.010
it's being successful
is connecting

00:04:51.010 --> 00:04:55.120
to the community in a way that
this play, a local playwright

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:57.940
and a local actor,
can help them do.

00:04:57.940 --> 00:04:59.330
JULIE: Yes, I would agree.

00:04:59.330 --> 00:05:03.940
And it's even more special when
the audience can really relate

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:06.110
and visually see the locations.

00:05:06.110 --> 00:05:09.550
I mean, in "The Great Leap,"
it's USF, it's Chinatown.

00:05:09.550 --> 00:05:12.070
Galileo High School
is also mentioned.

00:05:12.070 --> 00:05:14.602
And so they're already
along the ride for you.

00:05:14.602 --> 00:05:16.060
There's not-- I
mean, you obviously

00:05:16.060 --> 00:05:19.060
have to work for the story,
but it's kind of nice

00:05:19.060 --> 00:05:20.550
when they're already with you.

00:05:20.550 --> 00:05:21.842
BD WONG: When they're already--

00:05:21.842 --> 00:05:22.580
absolutely.

00:05:22.580 --> 00:05:25.820
And I had the really
good experience

00:05:25.820 --> 00:05:30.210
of doing this same play
in New York last year.

00:05:30.210 --> 00:05:34.490
And one of the major joys
of doing it again here

00:05:34.490 --> 00:05:37.970
is my seeing the difference
of how the audience reacts

00:05:37.970 --> 00:05:39.290
to certain things.

00:05:39.290 --> 00:05:41.840
And I love the way
the San Francisco

00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:45.578
audience responds to the San
Francisconess of the play.

00:05:45.578 --> 00:05:47.120
You can feel it,
and you can hear it,

00:05:47.120 --> 00:05:48.840
and it's really exciting.

00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:53.630
There's a line in the play
where the American basketball

00:05:53.630 --> 00:05:56.990
coach is telling the kid,
you know, I played and--

00:05:56.990 --> 00:06:01.040
I went to China and I coached
the Chinese basketball players.

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:03.470
And they don't want
to rough each other up

00:06:03.470 --> 00:06:05.620
and they don't want
to touch each other.

00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:07.370
I'm paraphrasing, but
that's what he says.

00:06:07.370 --> 00:06:10.280
And the kid says, have you
ever been to Chinatown?

00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:11.210
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:11.210 --> 00:06:13.550
And that line is a very
perfectly funny line

00:06:13.550 --> 00:06:15.500
in New York City,
but in San Francisco,

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:17.330
the audience just loves it.

00:06:17.330 --> 00:06:21.500
They just love knowing that the
playwright really knows what--

00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:22.127
JULIE: Yes.

00:06:22.127 --> 00:06:24.210
BD WONG: --pushy Chinese
people in Chinatown are--

00:06:24.210 --> 00:06:25.076
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:25.076 --> 00:06:26.950
--on the 30 Stockton are like.

00:06:26.950 --> 00:06:28.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:28.630 --> 00:06:29.942
JULIE: So true.

00:06:29.942 --> 00:06:31.760
So, so true.

00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:35.287
And you mentioned you did
this play in New York.

00:06:35.287 --> 00:06:36.870
And so this is the
second time around.

00:06:36.870 --> 00:06:40.280
What is it like to play the
character for the second time?

00:06:40.280 --> 00:06:42.980
BD WONG: It's great.

00:06:42.980 --> 00:06:45.785
Whenever you do a play
in a different theater,

00:06:45.785 --> 00:06:46.910
it's going to be different.

00:06:46.910 --> 00:06:49.970
But this is even more
so different than that,

00:06:49.970 --> 00:06:51.980
because it's a completely
different theater

00:06:51.980 --> 00:06:53.480
company that did the play.

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:56.150
It was completely different
director and different actors.

00:06:56.150 --> 00:07:02.180
So I'm the real only kind
of consistent thing in it.

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:05.780
And the other big difference
is that the theater

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:07.880
was very small in New York.

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:09.870
It was a 99 seat theater.

00:07:09.870 --> 00:07:11.750
And this is an
1,100 seat theater.

00:07:11.750 --> 00:07:16.125
And just technique-wise
and physically,

00:07:16.125 --> 00:07:17.750
it's a completely
different production.

00:07:17.750 --> 00:07:19.040
It's a big set.

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:21.860
This version is much
more like a Broadway show

00:07:21.860 --> 00:07:24.320
than the one we did in New
York, where Broadway is.

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:30.350
So that experience is
really a learning experience

00:07:30.350 --> 00:07:33.980
for somebody like me,
because you're always

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:35.840
surprised at the
new things that you

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:39.810
can discover when the play is
opened up in a much bigger way.

00:07:39.810 --> 00:07:40.850
JULIE: Right.

00:07:40.850 --> 00:07:42.530
BD WONG: Lots of
things, like there's--

00:07:42.530 --> 00:07:44.600
I have more costumes
in this production

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:46.260
than I had in the
first production.

00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:49.520
And usually you'd
think the play,

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:52.700
the storytelling of the play
requires certain characters

00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:54.980
to wear certain costumes
at certain times.

00:07:54.980 --> 00:07:58.670
And that's true, but I was able
to, because the theater was

00:07:58.670 --> 00:08:02.268
so small, wear the same thing
throughout the entire play.

00:08:02.268 --> 00:08:04.310
And it worked really well,
because that character

00:08:04.310 --> 00:08:09.200
was consistent throughout,
from 1971 to 1989.

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:11.990
This time, because it's
so opened up and big,

00:08:11.990 --> 00:08:14.210
when I walk off the stage
and I come back on again

00:08:14.210 --> 00:08:15.680
and it's a different
time period,

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:17.990
you kind of want to see
me dressed differently.

00:08:17.990 --> 00:08:19.865
JULIE: Yeah, you want
to see the progression.

00:08:19.865 --> 00:08:22.647
BD WONG: And so I was really
kind of thrown off at first.

00:08:22.647 --> 00:08:24.230
Like oh, I'm going
to wear all these--

00:08:24.230 --> 00:08:27.030
like the first day they show
you all the sketches and stuff.

00:08:27.030 --> 00:08:28.520
And I was really
surprised at that.

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:32.330
And then my mind had to
click over to, oh, I see.

00:08:32.330 --> 00:08:34.137
I see this differently now.

00:08:34.137 --> 00:08:36.679
And that is an example of a lot
of different things that have

00:08:36.679 --> 00:08:40.669
happened-- the way you use your
voice and all of that stuff--

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:45.350
that are adjustments and
learning experiences.

00:08:45.350 --> 00:08:47.270
JULIE: How has it
been just performing

00:08:47.270 --> 00:08:48.980
for some of the early audiences?

00:08:48.980 --> 00:08:50.515
I saw it during a
dress rehearsal,

00:08:50.515 --> 00:08:53.750
so I know that was the
first time you were up.

00:08:53.750 --> 00:08:59.630
BD WONG: Well, a play like this
with a lot of fast language

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:02.012
and a lot of--

00:09:02.012 --> 00:09:03.470
at least one of
the four characters

00:09:03.470 --> 00:09:07.820
in the play that has a lot of
movement, and a lot of staging.

00:09:07.820 --> 00:09:10.190
And then there's physical
elements in the production,

00:09:10.190 --> 00:09:12.540
like moving scenery
and stuff like that.

00:09:12.540 --> 00:09:15.830
These things take
such time to iron out.

00:09:15.830 --> 00:09:18.110
And so there's never
been such a thing

00:09:18.110 --> 00:09:21.440
as a perfectly brilliant
dress rehearsal,

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:23.840
because you're still
working things out.

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:26.360
You can never be that ahead
of schedule that by the time

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:29.000
the audience comes,
it's all down.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:30.970
Your mind is always
processing things.

00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:37.890
So we did a pretty clean
skate on that dress rehearsal,

00:09:37.890 --> 00:09:40.158
but the show has definitely
deepened and deepened

00:09:40.158 --> 00:09:40.700
and deepened.

00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:43.280
And we've done it maybe
six or seven times now.

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:45.830
And it's almost--
it's pretty much

00:09:45.830 --> 00:09:50.010
hit its stride as far as the
command that we have over it.

00:09:50.010 --> 00:09:50.552
JULIE: Right.

00:09:50.552 --> 00:09:52.343
BD WONG: And it's like
practicing anything,

00:09:52.343 --> 00:09:53.660
right, over and over again.

00:09:53.660 --> 00:09:56.395
The more you do it,
the better it gets.

00:09:56.395 --> 00:09:57.770
And with this kind
of play, which

00:09:57.770 --> 00:10:02.520
is kind of deep and kind of full
of lots of details and stuff,

00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:06.650
it's a kind of a
bottomless well, you know.

00:10:06.650 --> 00:10:09.110
You don't ever get bored of
it, because there's always

00:10:09.110 --> 00:10:11.180
something new to
discover about it.

00:10:11.180 --> 00:10:13.535
JULIE: That's the beauty of
theater and live production.

00:10:13.535 --> 00:10:15.260
BD WONG: Yeah, and
good plays, and plays

00:10:15.260 --> 00:10:17.215
that are written with
a kind of substance.

00:10:17.215 --> 00:10:19.590
JULIE: Especially when you're
in love with the play, too.

00:10:19.590 --> 00:10:20.300
BD WONG: Yeah, I do--

00:10:20.300 --> 00:10:21.550
JULIE: You do it all the time.

00:10:21.550 --> 00:10:22.140
BD WONG: I do.

00:10:22.140 --> 00:10:25.850
And this particular play
is one of my favorite plays

00:10:25.850 --> 00:10:27.530
that I've ever been able to do.

00:10:27.530 --> 00:10:29.100
I love doing it.

00:10:29.100 --> 00:10:31.100
I could keep doing it forever.

00:10:31.100 --> 00:10:35.630
I understand why actors like
Carol Channing and Yul Brynner

00:10:35.630 --> 00:10:37.670
played parts forever and ever.

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:39.320
I used to think
they were losers.

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:40.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:40.820 --> 00:10:42.710
I used to think, oh, god.

00:10:42.710 --> 00:10:45.590
Put it away, Carol.

00:10:45.590 --> 00:10:48.050
You're 80 years old.

00:10:48.050 --> 00:10:50.750
And she's going on tour with
another tour of "Hello Dolly."

00:10:50.750 --> 00:10:52.460
She maybe did seven--
and Yul Brynner--

00:10:52.460 --> 00:10:54.230
seven or eight tours of the--

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:58.280
but when that part sings for
you, you want to keep doing it.

00:10:58.280 --> 00:11:00.570
And you know what you're
giving the audience.

00:11:00.570 --> 00:11:02.090
And they're loving it.

00:11:02.090 --> 00:11:04.890
There's no way that you're
going to give that up.

00:11:04.890 --> 00:11:08.930
So I don't see myself continuing
to do this play until I'm 80,

00:11:08.930 --> 00:11:12.750
but I understand the joy that
one gets from that, yeah.

00:11:12.750 --> 00:11:13.250
JULIE: Yeah.

00:11:13.250 --> 00:11:14.540
I mean, you could
certainly do it,

00:11:14.540 --> 00:11:16.040
because it has that
age progression--

00:11:16.040 --> 00:11:16.957
BD WONG: Yes, it does.

00:11:16.957 --> 00:11:18.885
JULIE: --and you certainly
don't age at all.

00:11:18.885 --> 00:11:20.310
BD WONG: Yeah, OK.

00:11:20.310 --> 00:11:23.750
JULIE: [LAUGHS] What
I really walked away

00:11:23.750 --> 00:11:30.480
with from the play was that
it's about manifesting destiny.

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:34.880
And there's two
characters, and one

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:37.100
is able to just kind of
move through the world

00:11:37.100 --> 00:11:40.460
and say, yes, everything is
on my plate and I can grab it.

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:41.300
That's Manford.

00:11:41.300 --> 00:11:43.940
And for your character,
it's more or less

00:11:43.940 --> 00:11:46.940
like waiting for the
opportunity to be told,

00:11:46.940 --> 00:11:48.350
like, it's now your time.

00:11:48.350 --> 00:11:51.117
And there's a line
at the end where he--

00:11:51.117 --> 00:11:53.450
and I'm going to paraphrase
as well-- but like basically

00:11:53.450 --> 00:11:56.870
saying that I didn't
know that it was my time,

00:11:56.870 --> 00:11:58.340
but now it's my time.

00:11:58.340 --> 00:11:59.467
It's always been there.

00:11:59.467 --> 00:12:00.050
BD WONG: Yeah.

00:12:00.050 --> 00:12:02.600
JULIE: And I'm
wondering how that

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:06.420
parallels with your successful
career that you've had.

00:12:06.420 --> 00:12:07.820
BD WONG: Oh, wow.

00:12:07.820 --> 00:12:08.690
I never made a--

00:12:08.690 --> 00:12:13.490
I never thought to parallel it
that particularly personally.

00:12:13.490 --> 00:12:16.850
I have always
considered him someone

00:12:16.850 --> 00:12:20.210
that I needed to learn
about, because he,

00:12:20.210 --> 00:12:29.480
being a citizen of
Communist China, what

00:12:29.480 --> 00:12:34.430
was built into that life,
particularly in this time

00:12:34.430 --> 00:12:37.640
period, was a life of giving
yourself-- giving over

00:12:37.640 --> 00:12:40.010
your own wishes to the
wishes of the party

00:12:40.010 --> 00:12:42.980
and not making
choices for yourself.

00:12:42.980 --> 00:12:46.010
And what's a nice
juxtaposition in the play

00:12:46.010 --> 00:12:51.950
is that this balls to the
wall Asian-American kid who

00:12:51.950 --> 00:12:55.010
doesn't know anything
about that, just

00:12:55.010 --> 00:12:58.790
wants and is going
after his dream.

00:12:58.790 --> 00:12:59.350
JULIE: Yes.

00:12:59.350 --> 00:13:03.050
BD WONG: And in comparison,
this other character in China

00:13:03.050 --> 00:13:07.790
is giving up all of his
dreams, because there's

00:13:07.790 --> 00:13:12.260
no alternative for him because
of the political circumstances

00:13:12.260 --> 00:13:14.240
that he is in.

00:13:14.240 --> 00:13:18.080
Personally, I guess
what I could say

00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:20.030
is that when I was
in high school,

00:13:20.030 --> 00:13:26.810
I was just so lucky to have had
a very mentorial relationship

00:13:26.810 --> 00:13:31.490
with a high school drama teacher
who recognized potential in me

00:13:31.490 --> 00:13:39.110
and who absolutely
demanded that I follow it,

00:13:39.110 --> 00:13:42.350
or that I not squander it.

00:13:42.350 --> 00:13:46.610
To the point where she took me
by the hand to my own parents

00:13:46.610 --> 00:13:48.890
and said, I really
think this person

00:13:48.890 --> 00:13:53.760
needs to keep doing this.

00:13:53.760 --> 00:13:54.500
JULIE: Wow.

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:58.520
BD WONG: And my parents were
rather typical Asian-American

00:13:58.520 --> 00:14:00.470
second generation parents.

00:14:00.470 --> 00:14:02.720
They weren't super,
super, super--

00:14:02.720 --> 00:14:04.490
they weren't tiger parents.

00:14:04.490 --> 00:14:10.730
They were more, though,
conditioned and assumed

00:14:10.730 --> 00:14:12.680
that the best thing
for us would be

00:14:12.680 --> 00:14:16.640
successful and stable careers.

00:14:16.640 --> 00:14:18.273
Doctor or lawyer, that was it.

00:14:18.273 --> 00:14:18.960
That was it.

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:20.960
JULIE: Yes.

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:23.300
BD WONG: And so that
was a huge paradigm

00:14:23.300 --> 00:14:27.020
shift for this person who
was kind of an expert, right?

00:14:27.020 --> 00:14:27.560
She knew.

00:14:27.560 --> 00:14:28.820
She was a drama teacher.

00:14:28.820 --> 00:14:33.360
Not really, but she did have
credibility for my parents.

00:14:33.360 --> 00:14:37.950
And so the idea-- when you say
the idea of taking your shot,

00:14:37.950 --> 00:14:43.410
or looking, following your
bliss, or taking what you think

00:14:43.410 --> 00:14:46.950
could be yours, that
came from outside forces

00:14:46.950 --> 00:14:50.760
that I was lucky to
have been exposed to.

00:14:50.760 --> 00:14:53.370
And I guess I do
relate emotionally

00:14:53.370 --> 00:14:56.400
at the end of the
play to someone

00:14:56.400 --> 00:14:58.680
who isn't able to do that.

00:14:58.680 --> 00:15:03.720
And whatever the complicated
feelings that one

00:15:03.720 --> 00:15:07.710
has not having to have that
restriction, the guilt you

00:15:07.710 --> 00:15:10.660
might feel, survivor's
guilt kind of thing,

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:13.800
or it what if it
were me, really,

00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:15.920
we're all here just
because we're here.

00:15:15.920 --> 00:15:19.530
We don't get a choice to
be Communist Chinese or not

00:15:19.530 --> 00:15:21.030
Communist Chinese.

00:15:21.030 --> 00:15:22.710
And in this particular
play, it really

00:15:22.710 --> 00:15:25.136
shows that you
don't have a choice.

00:15:25.136 --> 00:15:26.390
JULIE: Yes.

00:15:26.390 --> 00:15:28.320
BD WONG: And so I
think we all kind

00:15:28.320 --> 00:15:30.690
of take for granted our
freedom and our ability

00:15:30.690 --> 00:15:35.090
to do whatever we want and
to say whatever we want.

00:15:35.090 --> 00:15:44.755
And the play very, very
beautifully reminds us of that.

00:15:44.755 --> 00:15:46.380
And I do like that
part about the play.

00:15:46.380 --> 00:15:50.550
So I do relate to the
character's inability

00:15:50.550 --> 00:15:57.120
to access his dreams based upon
my ability to access my dreams,

00:15:57.120 --> 00:15:57.720
I guess.

00:15:57.720 --> 00:15:58.950
JULIE: Yes.

00:15:58.950 --> 00:16:04.800
It's interesting
because a lot of times,

00:16:04.800 --> 00:16:09.030
even like if we take the context
out of the play of just being

00:16:09.030 --> 00:16:12.030
maybe an emerging
artist of color,

00:16:12.030 --> 00:16:15.390
or part of the LGBTQ
community, which you have been

00:16:15.390 --> 00:16:19.380
a huge advocate for both, I
think it's quite difficult when

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:24.430
we are going out to pursue
those kinds of artistic dreams,

00:16:24.430 --> 00:16:26.910
whether it be in acting,
dance, or even here in tech,

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:28.890
if you don't see
a role model, it's

00:16:28.890 --> 00:16:32.100
hard to really think
about, can I go out

00:16:32.100 --> 00:16:34.120
and grab hold of those dreams?

00:16:34.120 --> 00:16:36.560
And it was great that you
mentioned your high school

00:16:36.560 --> 00:16:37.060
mentor.

00:16:37.060 --> 00:16:39.540
But as someone who may
not have that, what

00:16:39.540 --> 00:16:41.970
is some advice that you would--

00:16:41.970 --> 00:16:44.490
BD WONG: Well, I--

00:16:44.490 --> 00:16:47.050
advice, I have tons of advice.

00:16:47.050 --> 00:16:49.830
But before I give advice,
I think it's-- and it is

00:16:49.830 --> 00:16:58.122
important to acknowledge that
phenomenon of representation.

00:16:58.122 --> 00:16:59.580
We're in this point
now where we're

00:16:59.580 --> 00:17:01.740
talking about
representation all the time.

00:17:01.740 --> 00:17:05.970
And it doesn't lose its meaning,
but what I love to talk about,

00:17:05.970 --> 00:17:09.450
what is absolutely essential
about that representation

00:17:09.450 --> 00:17:12.119
is the influence that
that representation has

00:17:12.119 --> 00:17:14.190
over younger people, right?

00:17:14.190 --> 00:17:15.750
And that what we're
really fighting

00:17:15.750 --> 00:17:18.900
for in our grown-up
state is, well, we

00:17:18.900 --> 00:17:19.900
want to see more Asians.

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:21.329
But I want to see--

00:17:21.329 --> 00:17:22.569
I want my stories to be told.

00:17:22.569 --> 00:17:25.290
I want to see sexy Asian
people on the screen and all

00:17:25.290 --> 00:17:25.960
of that stuff.

00:17:25.960 --> 00:17:30.300
But what we really want is
for the needle to shift,

00:17:30.300 --> 00:17:38.910
because our kids don't
have the same schism when

00:17:38.910 --> 00:17:42.210
it comes to looking,
searching fruitlessly

00:17:42.210 --> 00:17:44.220
for themselves in the media.

00:17:44.220 --> 00:17:47.730
And it is shifting in a way
where the exposure is greater

00:17:47.730 --> 00:17:48.510
now.

00:17:48.510 --> 00:17:50.800
And we do love that.

00:17:50.800 --> 00:17:53.300
And so my advice would
be, I don't know,

00:17:53.300 --> 00:17:55.530
I think it's partly--

00:17:55.530 --> 00:17:58.320
for me, it's always been
kind of that hokey Gandhi

00:17:58.320 --> 00:18:01.770
thing, that be the change
you want to see thing.

00:18:01.770 --> 00:18:04.530
That there's always someone
that you can mentor.

00:18:04.530 --> 00:18:06.660
There's always someone--
even if you're not famous,

00:18:06.660 --> 00:18:11.760
there's always someone that
is looking to you for--

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:13.920
and as role models,
I think people

00:18:13.920 --> 00:18:17.175
forget that that thing
is really happening.

00:18:17.175 --> 00:18:18.300
You don't see it happening.

00:18:18.300 --> 00:18:19.467
You don't feel it happening.

00:18:19.467 --> 00:18:21.690
But it's happening
Young people are

00:18:21.690 --> 00:18:27.150
looking to you for an example
of what they are going to be.

00:18:27.150 --> 00:18:29.590
They have no other
frame of reference

00:18:29.590 --> 00:18:32.760
but to see a person older and
more experienced than them

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:34.410
and to do as they do.

00:18:34.410 --> 00:18:35.220
JULIE: Yes

00:18:35.220 --> 00:18:39.480
BD WONG: And so our
self-esteem is super important

00:18:39.480 --> 00:18:42.330
and our sense of sorting
out all the baggage

00:18:42.330 --> 00:18:45.420
that our parents gave us and
their grandparents gave them.

00:18:45.420 --> 00:18:49.260
Sorting all that so that it's
a little bit easier for them

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:53.160
is a fun challenge, I
think, because we're still

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:54.450
dealing with our own baggage.

00:18:54.450 --> 00:18:57.310
But I think we do have
less, a little bit,

00:18:57.310 --> 00:18:58.870
than our grandparents had.

00:18:58.870 --> 00:18:59.920
JULIE: I hope so.

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:01.295
BD WONG: We have
different kinds.

00:19:01.295 --> 00:19:03.480
Our grandparents didn't
care about representation.

00:19:03.480 --> 00:19:04.260
JULIE: True.

00:19:04.260 --> 00:19:06.360
BD WONG: They don't
care at all about it.

00:19:06.360 --> 00:19:09.840
But then I do remember my
parents' generation of people

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:12.400
running into the
living room saying,

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:14.460
oh my god, look there's
an Asian person on TV,

00:19:14.460 --> 00:19:15.750
like that kind of thing.

00:19:15.750 --> 00:19:18.600
And us all running
into the living room.

00:19:18.600 --> 00:19:20.510
That wasn't that long ago.

00:19:20.510 --> 00:19:23.310
And there is still a
sense of that now, right?

00:19:23.310 --> 00:19:24.090
Oh, look.

00:19:24.090 --> 00:19:28.040
Wow, it's a commercial
with an Asian person in it.

00:19:28.040 --> 00:19:30.287
That's kind of a new
trend, commercials

00:19:30.287 --> 00:19:31.370
with Asian people in them.

00:19:31.370 --> 00:19:32.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:32.580 --> 00:19:34.650
Well, because for
whatever reason,

00:19:34.650 --> 00:19:38.010
we could talk about it
forever, about the misnomer

00:19:38.010 --> 00:19:40.162
that Asian people, their
money doesn't matter

00:19:40.162 --> 00:19:41.120
or something like that.

00:19:41.120 --> 00:19:42.245
JULIE: Something like that.

00:19:42.245 --> 00:19:44.946
BD WONG: So now it's
clearly true that--

00:19:44.946 --> 00:19:47.920
it's been established that
the money does matter.

00:19:47.920 --> 00:19:49.642
And that's good for us in a way.

00:19:49.642 --> 00:19:51.600
And it's certainly good
for our representation.

00:19:51.600 --> 00:19:52.560
JULIE: Oh, totally.

00:19:52.560 --> 00:19:55.445
Yeah, and I mean the success
with "Crazy Rich Asians,"

00:19:55.445 --> 00:19:57.570
I mean, proved that it can
be a commercial success.

00:19:57.570 --> 00:19:59.260
BD WONG: Right,
that it transcended

00:19:59.260 --> 00:20:02.323
being an Asian movie by being
popular across the board, yeah.

00:20:02.323 --> 00:20:03.240
JULIE: Everybody, yes.

00:20:03.240 --> 00:20:06.420
And that's what's really nice.

00:20:06.420 --> 00:20:09.930
I did hear on a podcast that you
did maybe a couple weeks ago,

00:20:09.930 --> 00:20:14.100
KQED, what really struck
me was you did talk

00:20:14.100 --> 00:20:16.230
about the responsibility
that you have,

00:20:16.230 --> 00:20:19.860
or producers, or people who
have that power of choosing

00:20:19.860 --> 00:20:23.340
the story, that they
have this responsibility

00:20:23.340 --> 00:20:27.450
to create these images and
characters so that the younger

00:20:27.450 --> 00:20:31.330
generation can be inspired.

00:20:31.330 --> 00:20:35.670
So I'm wondering, what is
your personal responsibility

00:20:35.670 --> 00:20:36.210
for that?

00:20:36.210 --> 00:20:39.530
Are you having a hand in
developing [INAUDIBLE]

00:20:39.530 --> 00:20:40.280
BD WONG: Oh, yeah.

00:20:40.280 --> 00:20:41.260
You mean what am I doing?

00:20:41.260 --> 00:20:41.760
JULIE: Yeah.

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:42.690
BD WONG: Yeah, I am.

00:20:42.690 --> 00:20:44.770
I think that's
one of the great--

00:20:44.770 --> 00:20:47.170
one of the things that
comes out of frustration

00:20:47.170 --> 00:20:50.560
is the creative limitations
that you're given.

00:20:50.560 --> 00:20:55.780
Create, if you're up
for it, opportunities

00:20:55.780 --> 00:20:57.970
for yourself, or for
others, or for the people

00:20:57.970 --> 00:21:00.850
that you believe in that are
experiencing the same kind

00:21:00.850 --> 00:21:03.690
of marginalization as you.

00:21:03.690 --> 00:21:05.305
And so I have--

00:21:05.305 --> 00:21:08.920
I'm always working
on things on my own,

00:21:08.920 --> 00:21:12.100
like trying to maintain my
relationship with theaters

00:21:12.100 --> 00:21:14.470
like ACT to kind of like--

00:21:14.470 --> 00:21:16.760
I'm already thinking,
now, what's next?

00:21:16.760 --> 00:21:18.190
What would I do here next?

00:21:18.190 --> 00:21:23.000
And coming up with, you
can't just pick one thing.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:24.670
You can't just go
to Pam MacKinnon,

00:21:24.670 --> 00:21:26.420
the artistic director,
and say, oh, here's

00:21:26.420 --> 00:21:27.910
the one thing I
want to do, do it.

00:21:27.910 --> 00:21:30.730
You have to give her
a landscape of things

00:21:30.730 --> 00:21:34.080
that might work and see whether
any of them appeal to her.

00:21:34.080 --> 00:21:40.210
And all of those things for
me involve Asian-Americans,

00:21:40.210 --> 00:21:46.390
or not just me or me as
a character playing--

00:21:46.390 --> 00:21:52.510
they're all explorations of
re-imaginations of classic work

00:21:52.510 --> 00:21:58.780
or new work itself that will
do what this play that we're

00:21:58.780 --> 00:22:02.050
doing now is doing.

00:22:02.050 --> 00:22:04.780
When I talk about
producers, I'm not

00:22:04.780 --> 00:22:06.865
sure exactly what
I said that time,

00:22:06.865 --> 00:22:10.960
or don't remember
exactly, but I do

00:22:10.960 --> 00:22:14.350
feel that there's this
phenomenon that we're all

00:22:14.350 --> 00:22:18.018
well aware of that's
very frustrating that we

00:22:18.018 --> 00:22:19.310
don't know what to do about it.

00:22:19.310 --> 00:22:21.520
And that is that
unless it affects you,

00:22:21.520 --> 00:22:23.920
you often don't want to do
anything about something.

00:22:23.920 --> 00:22:28.900
It's the kind of thing-- to
use a very brutal example,

00:22:28.900 --> 00:22:32.590
it's like the people that
are most championing cancer

00:22:32.590 --> 00:22:34.660
research and stuff
are people that cancer

00:22:34.660 --> 00:22:36.550
has touched themselves, right?

00:22:36.550 --> 00:22:41.290
And this is a kind of way,
in some ways, for people

00:22:41.290 --> 00:22:43.520
to choose the things
that mean most to them,

00:22:43.520 --> 00:22:45.010
which is a nice thing.

00:22:45.010 --> 00:22:47.480
However, when it
comes to Hollywood,

00:22:47.480 --> 00:22:51.610
the issue of diversity doesn't
ring true for a lot of people.

00:22:51.610 --> 00:22:54.500
And it kind of defines
white privilege,

00:22:54.500 --> 00:22:58.150
what we like to throw around,
this term of white privilege.

00:22:58.150 --> 00:23:03.100
Because a person has no
sense of what that damage

00:23:03.100 --> 00:23:06.640
or what that pain or what
that exclusion feels like.

00:23:06.640 --> 00:23:08.860
So the ones who are
doing it are doing it

00:23:08.860 --> 00:23:11.680
because they know they're
supposed to or whatever.

00:23:11.680 --> 00:23:15.670
So some way to get them to feel
that is the thing that I think

00:23:15.670 --> 00:23:20.170
is an interesting challenge,
to get them to understand,

00:23:20.170 --> 00:23:23.060
to take to heart.

00:23:23.060 --> 00:23:27.460
It's the equivalent of
going to a cancer benefit,

00:23:27.460 --> 00:23:29.740
like a big cancer
gala or something,

00:23:29.740 --> 00:23:33.040
and watching the
video that they show

00:23:33.040 --> 00:23:37.690
of what it means to a survivor
or to their family or whatever.

00:23:37.690 --> 00:23:40.240
And you're going, oh,
those are human beings.

00:23:40.240 --> 00:23:41.830
I relate to being a human being.

00:23:41.830 --> 00:23:44.140
That thing, I don't
have to have cancer

00:23:44.140 --> 00:23:46.390
to know that this is important.

00:23:46.390 --> 00:23:46.900
JULIE: Yeah.

00:23:46.900 --> 00:23:49.660
BD WONG: And that
kind of sharing

00:23:49.660 --> 00:23:52.390
of that, because there are
still so many producers

00:23:52.390 --> 00:23:54.642
and people that are borderline.

00:23:54.642 --> 00:23:57.100
They're either doing it because
they think they're supposed

00:23:57.100 --> 00:23:59.530
to-- and that's good, but
they're still not really

00:23:59.530 --> 00:24:00.190
feeling it--

00:24:00.190 --> 00:24:01.630
or they don't get it at all.

00:24:01.630 --> 00:24:03.550
It doesn't occur to them.

00:24:03.550 --> 00:24:06.670
And I'm fascinated by
that, because I personally

00:24:06.670 --> 00:24:09.400
am really--

00:24:09.400 --> 00:24:12.640
I don't consume a lot of
things that are all white.

00:24:12.640 --> 00:24:15.190
Like when I see something that
seems kind of like it's all

00:24:15.190 --> 00:24:18.730
white or doesn't have any
Asian people in it at all,

00:24:18.730 --> 00:24:19.700
I'm not as interested.

00:24:19.700 --> 00:24:22.780
I don't connect to it.

00:24:22.780 --> 00:24:26.640
And so, like I
watched the other day,

00:24:26.640 --> 00:24:28.440
I watched "Hidden
Figures," which everybody

00:24:28.440 --> 00:24:29.440
loves that movie, right?

00:24:29.440 --> 00:24:31.740
It's a great-- it's a
very satisfying movie.

00:24:31.740 --> 00:24:35.520
But I'm less moved by it.

00:24:35.520 --> 00:24:37.960
I feel left out of
it in some ways.

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:39.480
Because as we grew--

00:24:39.480 --> 00:24:42.670
as I've grown up, it was always
like, are you black or white?

00:24:42.670 --> 00:24:44.820
There was like a
kind of question

00:24:44.820 --> 00:24:48.190
that was a very strange one
to perceive people asking.

00:24:48.190 --> 00:24:49.657
Anyway, I don't know.

00:24:49.657 --> 00:24:51.490
That's just me going
on about that question.

00:24:51.490 --> 00:24:52.520
JULIE: I love it.

00:24:52.520 --> 00:24:53.782
BD WONG: OK, thanks.

00:24:53.782 --> 00:24:54.990
JULIE: It's very interesting.

00:24:54.990 --> 00:24:58.950
But I kind of want to tag back
on to what you just said about,

00:24:58.950 --> 00:25:00.280
well, I'm not a part of it.

00:25:00.280 --> 00:25:04.650
And I think that's the narrative
that a lot of Asian-Americans

00:25:04.650 --> 00:25:08.130
feel, that we're not part of
the main narrative in Hollywood.

00:25:08.130 --> 00:25:09.500
BD WONG: Right.

00:25:09.500 --> 00:25:11.600
JULIE: Kind of to tie
back to Lauren, and then--

00:25:11.600 --> 00:25:13.433
I know we're talking
about "The Great Leap,"

00:25:13.433 --> 00:25:17.100
but the "King of the Yees" made
a comment about, in marketing,

00:25:17.100 --> 00:25:19.020
there's the black
people marketing,

00:25:19.020 --> 00:25:19.410
the Hispanic people--

00:25:19.410 --> 00:25:20.040
BD WONG: That's right.

00:25:20.040 --> 00:25:20.855
She talks about it, yeah.

00:25:20.855 --> 00:25:22.688
JULIE: --marketing, and
then there's Asians.

00:25:22.688 --> 00:25:24.840
And we're all lumped into
the Caucasian marketing

00:25:24.840 --> 00:25:29.060
plan, which I thought was
a very interesting point.

00:25:29.060 --> 00:25:33.090
And I'm wondering, how do we
get more visibility out there?

00:25:33.090 --> 00:25:36.170
Like how do we raise our
voices and say, hey, we matter,

00:25:36.170 --> 00:25:40.770
or make more stories about us
because we want to watch it?

00:25:40.770 --> 00:25:43.560
BD WONG: Well, I would tie
that into my being here today,

00:25:43.560 --> 00:25:47.350
really, because what
I'm trying to do--

00:25:47.350 --> 00:25:49.560
I mean, the theater
wants me to come and talk

00:25:49.560 --> 00:25:50.880
about the show, which is great.

00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:52.297
And I love talking
about the show.

00:25:52.297 --> 00:25:54.870
But what I really want
to do is to create

00:25:54.870 --> 00:25:57.900
a situation in which
Asian people are really

00:25:57.900 --> 00:26:01.020
supporting their own content.

00:26:01.020 --> 00:26:03.840
Because the only way to
perpetuate that content

00:26:03.840 --> 00:26:06.780
is for it to be successful.

00:26:06.780 --> 00:26:12.390
And if Pam MacKinnon, the
Caucasian-American artistic

00:26:12.390 --> 00:26:14.940
director of American
Conservatory Theater,

00:26:14.940 --> 00:26:17.640
has a big dud with
this play, she's

00:26:17.640 --> 00:26:20.250
less likely to do another one.

00:26:20.250 --> 00:26:24.180
And then we're all more
likely to complain about it.

00:26:24.180 --> 00:26:26.670
And we're like, oh, well,
ACT, they don't ever do--

00:26:26.670 --> 00:26:27.780
well, did you go?

00:26:27.780 --> 00:26:29.300
Did you go see it?

00:26:29.300 --> 00:26:30.415
JULIE: Exactly.

00:26:30.415 --> 00:26:32.040
BD WONG: And for
Asian-American people,

00:26:32.040 --> 00:26:33.957
well, with a lot of
people, like human beings,

00:26:33.957 --> 00:26:36.990
they don't always understand
the gesture of that.

00:26:36.990 --> 00:26:39.870
Like doing your part, voting.

00:26:39.870 --> 00:26:41.610
All of that stuff.

00:26:41.610 --> 00:26:43.440
Yes, it does matter
that you vote.

00:26:43.440 --> 00:26:45.090
And yes, it does
matter that you buy

00:26:45.090 --> 00:26:49.950
a ticket to see a play if you
care about what the play can

00:26:49.950 --> 00:26:53.720
do for you, the things that
you're complaining about,

00:26:53.720 --> 00:26:57.030
that we all complain about.

00:26:57.030 --> 00:27:01.830
So that's an equation that I
think could be made more clear.

00:27:01.830 --> 00:27:02.640
And I love that.

00:27:02.640 --> 00:27:07.260
And I always try to
tell people, oh, just

00:27:07.260 --> 00:27:09.780
try to support the content.

00:27:09.780 --> 00:27:12.730
And we really did that in a big
way with "Crazy Rich Asians."

00:27:12.730 --> 00:27:13.230
JULIE: Yes.

00:27:13.230 --> 00:27:16.590
BD WONG: That was really
super gratifying to me,

00:27:16.590 --> 00:27:19.740
and reassuring to me,
and encouraging to me

00:27:19.740 --> 00:27:23.220
that this generation of
Asian-Americans put their money

00:27:23.220 --> 00:27:25.890
where their mouth was,
and created a sense,

00:27:25.890 --> 00:27:29.508
whether it's true or not,
that something has changed.

00:27:29.508 --> 00:27:31.800
Because there's a lot of
articles out there now saying,

00:27:31.800 --> 00:27:33.110
has it really changed?

00:27:33.110 --> 00:27:34.110
Or whatever is it.

00:27:34.110 --> 00:27:35.650
What will happen next?

00:27:35.650 --> 00:27:39.240
There's a fair amount of
"Crazy Rich Asian" knockoff

00:27:39.240 --> 00:27:42.087
action happening out there,
which is a really good sign--

00:27:42.087 --> 00:27:42.920
JULIE: That's great.

00:27:42.920 --> 00:27:44.460
BD WONG: --that--

00:27:44.460 --> 00:27:47.490
I'm not into knockoffs but
I'm into the representation--

00:27:47.490 --> 00:27:48.670
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:48.670 --> 00:27:50.550
--so I'll take it.

00:27:50.550 --> 00:27:52.470
But it's absolutely--
like there's

00:27:52.470 --> 00:27:54.240
going to be a couple
of television shows

00:27:54.240 --> 00:27:55.720
and all of that stuff.

00:27:55.720 --> 00:27:58.080
And that's really good.

00:27:58.080 --> 00:28:00.408
You do have to kind
of, in some ways,

00:28:00.408 --> 00:28:01.950
if you're really,
really responsible,

00:28:01.950 --> 00:28:06.720
you take note of the people that
are sponsoring Asian content

00:28:06.720 --> 00:28:08.760
and try to support them.

00:28:08.760 --> 00:28:12.600
That's what network
television is kind of--

00:28:12.600 --> 00:28:14.340
one thing that it
allows you to do

00:28:14.340 --> 00:28:17.970
is to see the corporations
and the companies that

00:28:17.970 --> 00:28:20.710
support the things that
we're trying to do.

00:28:20.710 --> 00:28:23.280
So we don't think
about that, right?

00:28:23.280 --> 00:28:24.670
I don't think
about it that much.

00:28:24.670 --> 00:28:28.710
I have to go, OK, oh look,
OK, so these people are

00:28:28.710 --> 00:28:33.982
sponsors of the whatever show.

00:28:33.982 --> 00:28:35.190
I don't know, whatever it is.

00:28:35.190 --> 00:28:38.130
I'm doing this Comedy Central
show with Aquafina in summer.

00:28:38.130 --> 00:28:39.120
JULIE: That's right.

00:28:39.120 --> 00:28:46.710
BD WONG: And I can't wait to see
who buys ad time on that show.

00:28:46.710 --> 00:28:48.600
JULIE: OK, last question.

00:28:48.600 --> 00:28:51.823
