00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:42.870
AUDIENCE: And I wanted to
talk-- you talked a lot

00:35:42.870 --> 00:35:43.800
about representation today.

00:35:43.800 --> 00:35:44.490
BD WONG: Yeah.

00:35:44.490 --> 00:35:46.323
AUDIENCE: I wanted to
talk a little bit more

00:35:46.323 --> 00:35:48.240
about the pipeline issue.

00:35:48.240 --> 00:35:50.952
And for me, I got
out of the game.

00:35:50.952 --> 00:35:52.410
And I'm very ashamed
to admit that.

00:35:52.410 --> 00:35:55.000
And it was really hard for me.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.570
But I had those
prototypical parents

00:35:57.570 --> 00:35:59.910
who were like, chase your
dream, chase your dream.

00:35:59.910 --> 00:36:02.495
And then it became, I
can't do this anymore.

00:36:02.495 --> 00:36:03.120
BD WONG: Right.

00:36:03.120 --> 00:36:06.660
AUDIENCE: So I guess my
question is, what would you

00:36:06.660 --> 00:36:10.440
say to all of the folks who now
are going into an industry that

00:36:10.440 --> 00:36:15.060
is just slightly more
friendly to folks like us

00:36:15.060 --> 00:36:16.612
to keep them in the
game, and to keep

00:36:16.612 --> 00:36:17.820
that side of the [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:17.820 --> 00:36:18.180
BD WONG: Oh, great.

00:36:18.180 --> 00:36:20.100
That is a really good
positive-based question.

00:36:20.100 --> 00:36:21.000
Thank you.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.370
And you know, good
things come from pain.

00:36:23.370 --> 00:36:25.560
And if your pain
created this question

00:36:25.560 --> 00:36:28.780
and changes somebody's life,
that's probably a good thing.

00:36:28.780 --> 00:36:31.140
But I will say that--
just before I answer--

00:36:31.140 --> 00:36:37.020
is that pain, that
rejection, and that shame

00:36:37.020 --> 00:36:38.410
are universal, right?

00:36:38.410 --> 00:36:40.320
They're not your own.

00:36:40.320 --> 00:36:45.060
And you have to blame,
really, the situation

00:36:45.060 --> 00:36:49.500
much more than yourself
for the outcome of that.

00:36:49.500 --> 00:36:53.457
You seem perfectly happy
now, so I trust that that's--

00:36:53.457 --> 00:36:54.290
AUDIENCE: We'll see.

00:36:54.290 --> 00:36:55.123
BD WONG: Yeah, yeah.

00:36:55.123 --> 00:36:56.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:56.700 --> 00:36:57.900
And what I would say--

00:36:57.900 --> 00:36:59.828
well, I wouldn't
say anything that's

00:36:59.828 --> 00:37:02.370
that different from what people
told me when I first started,

00:37:02.370 --> 00:37:04.090
when it was
considerably different,

00:37:04.090 --> 00:37:07.632
which was if you absolutely
have to do it, then do it.

00:37:07.632 --> 00:37:09.840
And if you don't, you should
think of something else.

00:37:09.840 --> 00:37:14.610
It's super difficult. It
messes with your mind.

00:37:14.610 --> 00:37:16.080
It messes with your self-esteem.

00:37:16.080 --> 00:37:19.770
It messes with your sense of
self-worth, your sense of what

00:37:19.770 --> 00:37:21.510
success means.

00:37:21.510 --> 00:37:23.460
And you have to be--

00:37:23.460 --> 00:37:25.860
you have to have an
extremely strong constitution

00:37:25.860 --> 00:37:30.810
and an extremely
accessible support system.

00:37:30.810 --> 00:37:34.770
And I feel like you're right
that the needle's moved

00:37:34.770 --> 00:37:36.930
to the point where
young people--

00:37:36.930 --> 00:37:39.630
you want to kind of
slap them for the things

00:37:39.630 --> 00:37:41.970
that they complain about, right?

00:37:41.970 --> 00:37:45.900
Because it was so much harder
before and it is so much--

00:37:45.900 --> 00:37:48.090
there's so much more
opportunity now.

00:37:48.090 --> 00:37:54.210
But with that opportunity
comes more competition.

00:37:54.210 --> 00:37:57.550
And I certainly feel that from
the beginning of my career,

00:37:57.550 --> 00:37:59.410
there was less competition.

00:37:59.410 --> 00:38:02.160
And the competition has
grown and the amount

00:38:02.160 --> 00:38:05.340
of younger people in
the industry has grown.

00:38:05.340 --> 00:38:08.460
But so, also, has the amount
of Asian-American writers

00:38:08.460 --> 00:38:10.620
and the amount of
producers and people

00:38:10.620 --> 00:38:13.290
that are actually making
influential choices.

00:38:13.290 --> 00:38:15.420
So I would just say
that they really

00:38:15.420 --> 00:38:17.700
should not take for granted--

00:38:17.700 --> 00:38:19.200
especially given
what you're saying.

00:38:19.200 --> 00:38:22.470
They should not take for granted
any progress that's been made.

00:38:22.470 --> 00:38:27.370
But you know, young people
are so clueless sometimes,

00:38:27.370 --> 00:38:30.900
and rightly so, because
we can't know anything

00:38:30.900 --> 00:38:32.700
that happened before us.

00:38:32.700 --> 00:38:35.220
We can hear about it and
we can take it to heart.

00:38:35.220 --> 00:38:41.160
When we talk to my son, who
was born in 2000, about 9/11,

00:38:41.160 --> 00:38:43.450
he understands
the gravity of it.

00:38:43.450 --> 00:38:45.780
He doesn't feel
the emotion of it.

00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:48.810
He wasn't there to
watch on television

00:38:48.810 --> 00:38:52.050
the absolute
devastation and the loss

00:38:52.050 --> 00:38:54.070
and the emotional feelings.

00:38:54.070 --> 00:38:57.240
So you guys know that this
show, "Come From Away,"

00:38:57.240 --> 00:38:59.610
came into town a few weeks ago.

00:38:59.610 --> 00:39:02.430
"Come From Away," is
centered around the day

00:39:02.430 --> 00:39:04.360
of 9/11 and the days after.

00:39:04.360 --> 00:39:07.260
And it's one thing where
if you're of a certain age

00:39:07.260 --> 00:39:09.300
and you're sitting in the
audience at that show,

00:39:09.300 --> 00:39:11.220
everyone in the
audience is having

00:39:11.220 --> 00:39:16.060
the same emotional experience,
which is a very rare thing.

00:39:16.060 --> 00:39:18.700
In Lauren's play,
she's having to explain

00:39:18.700 --> 00:39:22.780
certain really heavy things that
have happened in its history.

00:39:22.780 --> 00:39:25.120
And you get it
from understanding

00:39:25.120 --> 00:39:26.610
what she's taught you about it.

00:39:26.610 --> 00:39:29.170
"Come From Away" starts
and it says, today's 9/11,

00:39:29.170 --> 00:39:31.290
and everyone starts
crying immediately.

00:39:31.290 --> 00:39:33.010
And it's kind of great.

00:39:33.010 --> 00:39:35.950
Anybody born after 9/11
doesn't really understand.

00:39:35.950 --> 00:39:38.650
This is a tangent
to try to describe

00:39:38.650 --> 00:39:44.740
these rather adorable young
people that are becoming actors

00:39:44.740 --> 00:39:48.040
don't really understand
the things that

00:39:48.040 --> 00:39:51.250
were built on the backs
of other people, right?

00:39:51.250 --> 00:39:57.070
This is an ongoing discussion
about everything-- about AIDS,

00:39:57.070 --> 00:40:01.150
about gay people and AIDS,
and about the Holocaust,

00:40:01.150 --> 00:40:04.120
and everything major
that has ever happened,

00:40:04.120 --> 00:40:06.700
where every pain that any
generation has experienced

00:40:06.700 --> 00:40:11.030
is really hard for the
following generation to feel.

00:40:11.030 --> 00:40:13.420
So we cut them a
little bit of slack.

00:40:13.420 --> 00:40:15.970
And we try to kind of--

00:40:15.970 --> 00:40:18.340
for me, I think a
sense of discipline

00:40:18.340 --> 00:40:21.040
and a sense of entitlement.

00:40:21.040 --> 00:40:22.810
Discipline needs
to be encouraged

00:40:22.810 --> 00:40:26.290
and entitlement needs to
be kind of smacked out

00:40:26.290 --> 00:40:29.200
of people sometimes.

00:40:29.200 --> 00:40:34.090
But the advice I would give is
that it requires an absolutely

00:40:34.090 --> 00:40:37.000
steadfast constitution.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:40.360
And that there's great
joy to be had in it,

00:40:40.360 --> 00:40:42.340
and that there's
something actually

00:40:42.340 --> 00:40:43.750
kind of noble about it.

00:40:43.750 --> 00:40:46.960
There is a sense, that I learned
from my first acting teacher,

00:40:46.960 --> 00:40:50.170
that you are a messenger,
and that if the messages

00:40:50.170 --> 00:40:53.530
that you're giving are
true and are positive

00:40:53.530 --> 00:40:56.710
and they make people think
or they make people act

00:40:56.710 --> 00:40:58.780
differently, then
you've done something,

00:40:58.780 --> 00:41:02.570
or you've acted as an agent to
something actually happening.

00:41:02.570 --> 00:41:07.660
So it's not just kind
of glamour and acting

00:41:07.660 --> 00:41:09.130
and applause and
stuff like that.

00:41:09.130 --> 00:41:13.550
It could be rather
useful in society.

00:41:13.550 --> 00:41:14.450
So thank you.

00:41:14.450 --> 00:41:15.380
I appreciate that.

00:41:15.380 --> 00:41:16.330
JULIE: Thank you.

00:41:16.330 --> 00:41:17.640
We have a question over here.

00:41:17.640 --> 00:41:18.700
AUDIENCE: Hi, BD.

00:41:18.700 --> 00:41:20.110
Thanks again for coming out.

00:41:20.110 --> 00:41:21.730
Just wanted to
ask you a question

00:41:21.730 --> 00:41:24.460
as an Asian-American
who's also grown up

00:41:24.460 --> 00:41:28.270
with second generation parents.

00:41:28.270 --> 00:41:32.620
If you ever traveled back to
China, if and when you did,

00:41:32.620 --> 00:41:34.000
did you ever--

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:35.650
how was that experience for you?

00:41:35.650 --> 00:41:38.590
And how were you
channel that when

00:41:38.590 --> 00:41:41.380
you're acting during the play?

00:41:41.380 --> 00:41:45.760
BD WONG: I went to
China two major times.

00:41:45.760 --> 00:41:48.820
The first time I went,
my dad was still alive.

00:41:48.820 --> 00:41:51.850
And I was booked to
be the guest speaker

00:41:51.850 --> 00:41:54.380
on a cruise that went to China.

00:41:54.380 --> 00:41:58.270
And it was a super-duper,
hilariously fancy cruise

00:41:58.270 --> 00:42:01.420
with all super old white people.

00:42:01.420 --> 00:42:06.250
But I was supposed to talk about
being a Chinese person to them.

00:42:06.250 --> 00:42:08.440
I was like-- it was a
little bit like a zoo.

00:42:08.440 --> 00:42:09.790
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:09.790 --> 00:42:12.430
You know, it's like
feeding time is at 4:15.

00:42:12.430 --> 00:42:17.130
BD Wong will come out and you
can throw pretzels at him.

00:42:17.130 --> 00:42:19.480
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:19.480 --> 00:42:23.710
But it was a really, really, in
many ways, moving experience.

00:42:23.710 --> 00:42:29.020
My dad had not been back to Hong
Kong since he left Hong Kong.

00:42:29.020 --> 00:42:33.160
Oddly enough, my grandfather
was born in California.

00:42:33.160 --> 00:42:36.550
My grandfather went back
home to marry my grandma

00:42:36.550 --> 00:42:39.160
and to have my dad and
then brought them back.

00:42:39.160 --> 00:42:43.000
So my dad was technically
not born here,

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:46.560
but he was born a citizen.

00:42:46.560 --> 00:42:48.940
And so he had this
very, like, oh my gosh,

00:42:48.940 --> 00:42:51.740
this is where I was born kind
of thing that really snuck up

00:42:51.740 --> 00:42:52.240
on him.

00:42:52.240 --> 00:42:54.470
I don't think he ever even
thought about going back,

00:42:54.470 --> 00:42:55.720
but here was this opportunity.

00:42:55.720 --> 00:42:56.290
We went back.

00:42:56.290 --> 00:42:58.460
So that was that.

00:42:58.460 --> 00:43:03.127
And I wish I could talk for
an hour about this cruise.

00:43:03.127 --> 00:43:04.210
It was so funny, because--

00:43:04.210 --> 00:43:04.680
JULIE: Sounds amazing.

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:06.513
BD WONG: Well, first
of all, I will tell you

00:43:06.513 --> 00:43:10.270
that the one thing is it was
so fancy that they give you

00:43:10.270 --> 00:43:12.850
this little thing to fill
out when you come in,

00:43:12.850 --> 00:43:14.170
when you check into your room.

00:43:14.170 --> 00:43:16.570
And the thing asks you
what kind of liquor

00:43:16.570 --> 00:43:22.270
they want you to stock the bar
with, the refrigerator with.

00:43:22.270 --> 00:43:25.330
And you get four bottles of
each, or something like that.

00:43:25.330 --> 00:43:27.880
And my mom is a
white wine drinker

00:43:27.880 --> 00:43:29.230
and my dad was a Jack Daniels.

00:43:29.230 --> 00:43:29.570
Drinker.

00:43:29.570 --> 00:43:31.153
So they got four
bottles of white wine

00:43:31.153 --> 00:43:32.770
and four bottles
of Jack Daniels.

00:43:32.770 --> 00:43:38.850
And then that night they put all
eight bottles in their suitcase

00:43:38.850 --> 00:43:40.730
and they filled
out the form again.

00:43:40.730 --> 00:43:41.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:41.230 --> 00:43:42.460
JULIE: Of course.

00:43:42.460 --> 00:43:45.130
BD WONG: By the
end of the cruise,

00:43:45.130 --> 00:43:49.870
they had like a
BevMo under the bed.

00:43:49.870 --> 00:43:52.666
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:54.070 --> 00:43:56.350
I don't want to say--

00:43:56.350 --> 00:43:57.970
it's racial profiling
to say that this

00:43:57.970 --> 00:44:00.940
is because they're Chinese.

00:44:00.940 --> 00:44:03.340
But no pun intended.

00:44:03.340 --> 00:44:04.825
You do the math.

00:44:04.825 --> 00:44:07.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:07.150 --> 00:44:10.270
I went on a second
trip to China in 2003

00:44:10.270 --> 00:44:12.740
to make a terrible
television movie.

00:44:12.740 --> 00:44:15.268
But that was a really
interesting cultural experience

00:44:15.268 --> 00:44:17.060
for me as well, working
with Chinese people

00:44:17.060 --> 00:44:23.390
and working in the Chinese
film industry in rural China.

00:44:23.390 --> 00:44:28.310
And I think, really, I hope
you'll come see the play.

00:44:28.310 --> 00:44:30.410
Lauren talks about the
experience of being

00:44:30.410 --> 00:44:34.160
an Asian-American and going
to China as a very unique kind

00:44:34.160 --> 00:44:36.800
of odd fish-out-of-water
experience.

00:44:36.800 --> 00:44:38.450
And that is THE
experience I felt.

00:44:38.450 --> 00:44:41.630
I didn't really feel like I
was home or anything like that.

00:44:41.630 --> 00:44:46.310
I felt-- it's so obvious to them
that you're American before you

00:44:46.310 --> 00:44:48.530
even open your mouth.

00:44:48.530 --> 00:44:50.660
You just, you can't hide it.

00:44:50.660 --> 00:44:55.190
And so there's always either a
curiosity or a slight disdain

00:44:55.190 --> 00:44:56.450
over you.

00:44:56.450 --> 00:44:59.330
And so I felt that tension.

00:44:59.330 --> 00:45:01.010
And that was no
different than the way

00:45:01.010 --> 00:45:07.280
that the young woman in the play
describes it in Lauren's play.

00:45:07.280 --> 00:45:08.810
So apparently,
Lauren understands

00:45:08.810 --> 00:45:10.760
that kind of experience too.

00:45:10.760 --> 00:45:13.220
It's pretty common.

00:45:13.220 --> 00:45:14.720
Did I answer the question?

00:45:14.720 --> 00:45:15.330
Not really.

00:45:15.330 --> 00:45:17.288
AUDIENCE: You did, or kind of.

00:45:17.288 --> 00:45:18.113
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:18.113 --> 00:45:20.030
BD WONG: You said good
things, but you did not

00:45:20.030 --> 00:45:20.840
answer the question.

00:45:20.840 --> 00:45:21.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:21.340 --> 00:45:23.370
JULIE: But we learned
about the BevMo.

00:45:23.370 --> 00:45:25.820
BD WONG: What was the
specific question?

00:45:25.820 --> 00:45:28.648
I can answer it now.

00:45:28.648 --> 00:45:29.440
AUDIENCE: I guess--

00:45:29.440 --> 00:45:31.480
BD WONG: Oh, how did I
draw on it in the play?

00:45:31.480 --> 00:45:33.633
Well, I would say that--

00:45:33.633 --> 00:45:35.050
how did I draw on
it for the play.

00:45:35.050 --> 00:45:37.630
I did really relate
it to Lauren's words

00:45:37.630 --> 00:45:40.280
about being an Asian-American
going to China.

00:45:40.280 --> 00:45:44.110
And I think what I had to do,
really, the research about how

00:45:44.110 --> 00:45:50.140
shut down a Chinese
person who's not

00:45:50.140 --> 00:45:54.790
a dream seeker, a person who is
of a certain constitution who

00:45:54.790 --> 00:45:58.120
is a party member of the--
a member of the party

00:45:58.120 --> 00:46:01.360
and very obedient
and very diligent.

00:46:01.360 --> 00:46:04.290
That is a very different
kind of person than me.

00:46:04.290 --> 00:46:08.500
And so I did have
to kind of access

00:46:08.500 --> 00:46:11.800
whatever else I
feel in my life that

00:46:11.800 --> 00:46:16.690
shuts me down, or quiets me, or
keeps me from making decisions.

00:46:16.690 --> 00:46:22.510
And I do relate to feeling like
a younger man being closeted

00:46:22.510 --> 00:46:26.770
and feeling kind of restricted
by my sense of being closeted,

00:46:26.770 --> 00:46:29.140
and a sense of not being
able to be free and open

00:46:29.140 --> 00:46:32.920
and speak my own truth.

00:46:32.920 --> 00:46:34.850
So that's the thing
I would relate to,

00:46:34.850 --> 00:46:37.937
I think, more than going
to China, actually.

00:46:37.937 --> 00:46:38.770
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:46:38.770 --> 00:46:39.353
BD WONG: Sure.

00:46:39.353 --> 00:46:40.062
JULIE: Thank you.

00:46:40.062 --> 00:46:42.794
BD WONG: I'm just going back and
forth, because it makes sense.

00:46:42.794 --> 00:46:44.150
AUDIENCE: Awesome.

00:46:44.150 --> 00:46:45.730
So I think a lot about inequity.

00:46:45.730 --> 00:46:46.748
It's a very heavy topic.

00:46:46.748 --> 00:46:47.290
BD WONG: Yes.

00:46:47.290 --> 00:46:49.220
AUDIENCE: I think a
lot about inequity.

00:46:49.220 --> 00:46:51.053
And one thing I've been
thinking a lot about

00:46:51.053 --> 00:46:53.680
is the importance of
Asian-Americans needing

00:46:53.680 --> 00:46:55.180
to leverage their
privilege in order

00:46:55.180 --> 00:46:57.788
to stand in deep solidarity
with other communities of color.

00:46:57.788 --> 00:46:59.080
So black and brown communities.

00:46:59.080 --> 00:47:01.690
And I know, obviously, there's
a nuance in various industries.

00:47:01.690 --> 00:47:04.920
I think the tech industry,
we're highly represented here.

00:47:04.920 --> 00:47:06.760
And that looks different
in other places.

00:47:06.760 --> 00:47:08.500
But I wanted to hear
a little bit more

00:47:08.500 --> 00:47:12.550
from you around how you think
about Asian-Americans building

00:47:12.550 --> 00:47:15.010
that solidarity with
other communities of color

00:47:15.010 --> 00:47:16.840
in the entertainment
industry, and what you

00:47:16.840 --> 00:47:18.490
see happening on that front.

00:47:18.490 --> 00:47:20.890
BD WONG: It's such
a wide reaching,

00:47:20.890 --> 00:47:22.840
far reaching industry, right?

00:47:22.840 --> 00:47:24.790
You have Hollywood.

00:47:24.790 --> 00:47:27.880
And here we are, I'm working
at a regional theater.

00:47:27.880 --> 00:47:31.420
And the regional theater has
its own agenda and aspirations

00:47:31.420 --> 00:47:35.620
for community building and for
community fundraising and all

00:47:35.620 --> 00:47:36.680
of that stuff.

00:47:36.680 --> 00:47:38.390
And they're different, I think.

00:47:38.390 --> 00:47:47.260
The wider Hollywood industry
is driven by a bottom line

00:47:47.260 --> 00:47:51.910
kind of thing that makes it
really hard for this needle

00:47:51.910 --> 00:47:53.113
to shift.

00:47:53.113 --> 00:47:55.030
And I don't know if
actually this-- this might

00:47:55.030 --> 00:47:56.950
be a similar kind of tangent.

00:47:56.950 --> 00:47:59.470
But what your question
is reminding me of

00:47:59.470 --> 00:48:03.880
is my own baggage
about fundraising,

00:48:03.880 --> 00:48:06.640
like for example, when I'm
pushing up the mountain

00:48:06.640 --> 00:48:08.380
several of my own projects.

00:48:08.380 --> 00:48:10.960
I've co-written a
musical that I'm

00:48:10.960 --> 00:48:14.420
trying to continue to develop.

00:48:14.420 --> 00:48:18.650
And I have, say,
several other projects,

00:48:18.650 --> 00:48:20.290
a lot of theater projects.

00:48:20.290 --> 00:48:21.640
And I find myself--

00:48:24.370 --> 00:48:27.950
one of them is one that our
friend has been involved in,

00:48:27.950 --> 00:48:33.280
a mutual friend, which is a
very diverse cast of actors.

00:48:33.280 --> 00:48:37.150
And other projects are
Asian-American projects.

00:48:37.150 --> 00:48:40.360
And I find myself
trying to edit myself

00:48:40.360 --> 00:48:42.550
when it comes to whose
money I'm going after.

00:48:42.550 --> 00:48:44.230
Like I [INAUDIBLE]
think, oh, you

00:48:44.230 --> 00:48:45.730
can't ask an
Asian-American person

00:48:45.730 --> 00:48:48.340
to help me fund the
diverse project.

00:48:48.340 --> 00:48:50.590
You should really be getting
the Asian-American person

00:48:50.590 --> 00:48:52.752
to fund the
Asian-American project.

00:48:52.752 --> 00:48:54.460
But I think, well,
wait a second, though,

00:48:54.460 --> 00:48:57.310
but I'm the Asian-American
making this project.

00:48:57.310 --> 00:49:00.760
Will that be enough
for them to support me,

00:49:00.760 --> 00:49:03.550
to help move the
needle in that way,

00:49:03.550 --> 00:49:09.700
because my work as a writer
will be put on the map.

00:49:09.700 --> 00:49:13.780
And then I will be able
to have the credibility

00:49:13.780 --> 00:49:15.590
to create more and more content.

00:49:15.590 --> 00:49:18.100
And as it turns out, this
particular diverse project

00:49:18.100 --> 00:49:21.430
ends up having a lot
of Asian people in it.

00:49:21.430 --> 00:49:23.620
But it's not an Asian project.

00:49:23.620 --> 00:49:26.260
And so is there a kind of--

00:49:26.260 --> 00:49:27.950
what I'm saying
is that I perceive

00:49:27.950 --> 00:49:32.140
there to be some kind
of invisible limit

00:49:32.140 --> 00:49:33.610
to the amount of
support I can get

00:49:33.610 --> 00:49:36.020
from the Asian-American
community,

00:49:36.020 --> 00:49:37.897
like from Asian people
that have money.

00:49:37.897 --> 00:49:40.480
I think, oh, I have to be really
careful about who I ask money

00:49:40.480 --> 00:49:42.120
for and what it's for.

00:49:42.120 --> 00:49:45.520
They'll want me to just--

00:49:45.520 --> 00:49:48.860
they'll want me to just do
all Asian content I think.

00:49:48.860 --> 00:49:51.130
And so that's interesting,
because I guess what I--

00:49:51.130 --> 00:49:52.460
as am repeating it--

00:49:52.460 --> 00:49:55.840
I'm an Asian-American artist
and that's the content

00:49:55.840 --> 00:49:56.673
that I'm generating.

00:49:56.673 --> 00:49:58.757
But I know that doesn't
really specifically answer

00:49:58.757 --> 00:49:59.350
your question.

00:49:59.350 --> 00:50:03.160
I'm also just me and I don't
really understand or know

00:50:03.160 --> 00:50:04.990
what's going on out
there, necessarily,

00:50:04.990 --> 00:50:11.020
about the connections between
different groups and how--

00:50:11.020 --> 00:50:16.154
You know, Ken Savage,
who was up here before--

00:50:16.154 --> 00:50:17.680
no, was he up here yet?

00:50:17.680 --> 00:50:18.790
No, he wasn't up here yet.

00:50:18.790 --> 00:50:23.280
Ken Savage, who works at ACT
and brought me here today,

00:50:23.280 --> 00:50:25.810
